### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: Mara has 150 - 40 = <<150-40=110>>110 cards.<n>Janet has 110/2 = <<110/2=55>>55 cards since Mara has twice as many as Janet.<n>Brenda has 55 - 9 = <<55-9=46>>46 cards since Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda.<n>Therefore, they all have 110 + 55 + 46 = <<110+55+46=211>>211 cards.<n>So the final answer is 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. He rode the bus 20 blocks to the post office to get some stamps. Later, he came home the same way. How many blocks did Pete travel in all?<n>Output: The number of blocks traveled on the way to the post office was 5 + 20 = <<5+20=25>>25.<n>Pete traveled 25 × 2 = <<25*2=50>>50 blocks in all.<n>So the final answer is 50<n><n>Input: In a classroom, there are blue chairs, green chairs, and white chairs. There are 10 blue chairs. The green chairs are 3 times as many as the blue chairs, and there are 13 fewer white chairs than the green and blue chairs combined. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: There are 10 x 3 = <<10*3=30>>30 green chairs.<n>The total number of blue and green chairs is 10 + 30 = <<10+30=40>>40.<n>So, there are 40 - 13 = <<40-13=27>>27 white chairs.<n>Therefore, there are 40 +27 = <<40+27=67>>67 chairs in a classroom.<n>So the final answer is 67<n><n>Input: 4.5 gallons of coffee were divided among 18 thermoses. Genevieve drank 3 thermoses. How many pints of coffee did Genevieve drink?<n>Output: 4.5 gallons = 4.5 * 8 pints = <<4.5*8=36>>36 pints<n>36/18 = <<36/18=2>>2 pints<n>Genevieve drank 2*3=<<2*3=6>>6 pints of coffee.<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Alannah, Beatrix, and Queen are preparing for the new school year and have been given books by their parents. Alannah has 20 more books than Beatrix. Queen has 1/5 times more books than Alannah. If Beatrix has 30 books, how many books do the three have together?<n>Output: If Beatrix has 30 books, Alannah has 30 books + 20 books = <<30+20=50>>50 books.<n>Queen has 1/5 * 50 books = <<1/5*50=10>>10 more books than Alannah.<n>The total number of books Queen has is 50 books + 10 books = <<50+10=60>>60 books.<n>All three have 60 books + 50 books + 30 books = <<60+50+30=140>>140 books together<n>So the final answer is 140<n><n>Input: A bird eats 7 berries a day. Samuel has 5 birds. How many berries do Samuel's birds eat in 4 days?<n>Output: A bird eats 7 x 4 = <<7*4=28>>28 berries in 4 days.<n>So, 5 birds can eat 28 x 5 = <<28*5=140>>140 berries in 4 days.<n>So the final answer is 140<n><n>Input:Google Maps and other highway and street GPS services have replaced what? Choices:  A: united states B: mexico C: countryside D: atlas E: oceans<n>Output:		Google Maps and other highway and<n>street GPS services have replaced A: United States <--Because they help people travel and go places around the world<n><n>## Answer my questions:<n><n>* What kind of animal is an anaconda?<n><n>- A snake<n><n>* What part of a cat's brain makes this animal cute?<n><n>- I don't know<n><n>* What are some examples of the following?<n><n>- Cat, dog, bird, animal, mammal, fish<n><n>* In each of the sentences below, replace the italicized words or phrase with one of the following words: dog, cat<n><n>- A dog is man's best friend. - <--Dog, It is a dog<n><n>- No dog is faster than this dog - <--Is dog fastest<n><n>- This dog looks very dangerous. - <--dog dangerous<n>

Remember that your program must be a function.<n>Program:#include <iostream><n>// This function takes an integer from the user, which is the first parameter. <n>int multiply(int num1, int num2);<n>// Here is the function that multiplies x and y for the <n>// user. <n>int multiply()<n>{<n>  int num1, num2, y, temp;<n>  cin>>num1>>num2; // Input numbers. <n>  temp =num1*num2; // Create temporary variable, for adding. <n>  y= temp - num1 + num2;<n>  return(y); // Return.<n>}<n>// The main function. <n>int main()<n>{<n>  // Here you will give the user the opportunity to call the <n>  // multiply() function. <n>  int num1;<n>  cin>> num1; // Input numbers from user. <n>  num1= num1; // The number of the person. <n>  multiply(num1,4); // Call multiply() function.  // The result will be displayed to the user. <n>}<n>```<n><n>### 콘텐츠 구조 설계 입니다<n><n>### 회원 등록<n>| 언어  | 영화 주제  | 영화명  | 이름  | 아이디  | 이때마다 1점 | 이

How many berries do Samuel's birds eat in 4 days?<n>Output: A bird eats 7 x 4 = <<7*4=28>>28 berries in 4 days.<n>So, 5 birds can eat 28 x 5 = <<28*5=140>>140 berries in 4 days.<n>So the final answer is 140<n><n>Input:Too many people want exotic snakes.  The demand is driving what to carry them? Choices:  A: ditch B: shop C: north america D: pet shops E: outdoors<n>Output:		There are too many people demanding snakes. Therefore, there is less supply. <n>Since the supply is less and the demand is higher, the snake sellers may decide to shop instead of ditch them.<n>Or they may sell them as pets and not outdoors.<n>Because E is not possible, this leaves choices A, B, C, and D.<n>E is not possible so we can delete that option.<n>Option A and C are impossible since it is said the people are demanding snakes, so A means the snake sellers dropped the snakes. So we can assume D is the option which has all of these things.<n>So the final option is D: pet shops<n>So the final answer for choice A is ditch.<n>So the final choice is D: pet shopps<n><n>Input: The population of a forest grew as more rabbits moved in. One of the rabbits noticed that the food supply had grown. Now there are more deer, rabbits, and owls in the forest, and 23 less snails than originally there. How many snails were there originally?<n>Output: 23 = 23/6(number of snails in forest)<n>1 deer eats 1 rabbit every 2 days.<n>1 rabbit eats 6 snails every 6 days ((1 / 6 since there are 6 snails per day)<n>1 owl eats 1 deer every 8 days.<n>The population of the forest is 7/8(number of deer + rabbits + owls).<n>Therefore, original number of food snails was (7/8)(23) = (7/8) 18.5.<n>Since we know 23 is the original #, this means that the original # of snails is 18.5 + 23 = 41.5.<n>So the number of snails was 41.5<n>So the answer for choice B is deer (7/8 deer)<n><n><n>Input: <n>Choices:  A: <n>Choices to be rejected: <n>Input: <n>So the answer for option A is rabbit and deer<n><n>Input:<n>Choices: b) <n>Choices to delete: <n>Input:<n>Since it is possible for us to get to the
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: Mara has 150 - 40 = <<150-40=110>>110 cards.<n>Janet has 110/2 = <<110/2=55>>55 cards since Mara has twice as many as Janet.<n>Brenda has 55 - 9 = <<55-9=46>>46 cards since Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda.<n>Therefore, they all have 110 + 55 + 46 = <<110+55+46=211>>211 cards.<n>So the final answer is 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. He rode the bus 20 blocks to the post office to get some stamps. Later, he came home the same way. How many blocks did Pete travel in all?<n>Output: The number of blocks traveled on the way to the post office was 5 + 20 = <<5+20=25>>25.<n>Pete traveled 25 × 2 = <<25*2=50>>50 blocks in all.<n>So the final answer is 50<n><n>Input: In a classroom, there are blue chairs, green chairs, and white chairs. There are 10 blue chairs. The green chairs are 3 times as many as the blue chairs, and there are 13 fewer white chairs than the green and blue chairs combined. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: There are 10 x 3 = <<10*3=30>>30 green chairs.<n>The total number of blue and green chairs is 10 + 30 = <<10+30=40>>40.<n>So, there are 40 - 13 = <<40-13=27>>27 white chairs.<n>Therefore, there are 40 +27 = <<40+27=67>>67 chairs in a classroom.<n>So the final answer is 67<n><n>Input: 4.5 gallons of coffee were divided among 18 thermoses. Genevieve drank 3 thermoses. Alannah has 20 more books than Beatrix. Queen has 1/5 times more books than Alannah. If Beatrix has 30 books, how many books do the three have together?<n>Output: If Beatrix has 30 books, Alannah has 30 books + 20 books = <<30+20=50>>50 books.<n>Queen has 1/5 * 50 books = <<1/5*50=10>>10 more books than Alannah.<n>The total number of books Queen has is 50 books + 10 books = <<50+10=60>>60 books.<n>All three have 60 books + 50 books + 30 books = <<60+50+30=140>>140 books together<n>So the final answer is 140<n><n>Input: A bird eats 7 berries a day. Samuel has 5 birds. How many upstairs shams are covered?<n>Output: The answer is Choice B<n><n>input:<n>There are 5 books on 2 shelves, and there are more books on the first shelf than on the second shelf. 5 books on two shelves means that there are two different combinations for books of different number of shelves. i.e. 5 books on one shelf means that there is one number to choose from, so let's imagine that 5 books are on one shelf.<n>There is another possibility which is like this: 5 books on the second shelf means that there are more than one numbers to choose from. So let's imagine there are two different books.<n>There is the first possibility(3 books on the second shelve) which we imagine we have chosen. Now we have 3 books on the second and first shelves. According to our choices, 3 and 2 are chosen. Now it's like this that 3 and 2 have been chosen, therefore the second possibility is that there are 3 books on the first shelve and 2 books on the second shelves. so if we consider that there has been a choice between both 3 or 2, then it's obvious that there will be 3 books on the FIRST shelf and 2 books on SECOND shelf.<n><n>The answer is 5 books on the FIRRST shelf.<n><n>Input: There is a house with 30 rooms. Twenty rooms contain an item of clothing. If you can count 15 of the rooms, how many clothing items are there?<n>Output: The total number of clothing items is 20. The number of rooms with clothing is also 20.<n>Because of this, the total number of rooms remaining is 10.<n>Then, if there are 15 rooms, there are 15/10 of the rooms occupied with clothing items.<n>So, in there are 20/10 = <<20/10=2>>2 rooms left without clothing items.<n>

There are 10 blue chairs. The green chairs are 3 times as many as the blue chairs, and there are 13 fewer white chairs than the green and blue chairs combined. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: There are 10 x 3 = <<10*3=30>>30 green chairs.<n>The total number of blue and green chairs is 10 + 30 = <<10+30=40>>40.<n>So, there are 40 - 13 = <<40-13=27>>27 white chairs.<n>Therefore, there are 40 +27 = <<40+27=67>>67 chairs in a classroom.<n>So the final answer is 67<n><n>Input: 4.5 gallons of coffee were divided among 18 thermoses. Genevieve drank 3 thermoses. How many pints of coffee did Genevieve drink?<n>Output: 4.5 gallons = 4.5 * 8 pints = <<4.5*8=36>>36 pints<n>36/18 = <<36/18=2>>2 pints<n>Genevieve drank 2*3=<<2*3=6>>6 pints of coffee.<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Alannah, Beatrix, and Queen are preparing for the new school year and have been given books by their parents. Alannah has 20 more books than Beatrix. Queen has 1/5 times more books than Alannah. If Beatrix has 30 books, how many books do the three have together?<n>Output: If Beatrix has 30 books, Alannah has 30 books + 20 books = <<30+20=50>>50 books.<n>Queen has 1/5 * 50 books = <<1/5*50=10>>10 more books than Alannah.<n>The total number of books Queen has is 50 books + 10 books = <<50+10=60>>60 books.<n>All three have 60 books + 50 books + 30 books = <<60+50+30=140>>140 books together<n>So the final answer is 140<n><n>Input: A bird eats 7 berries a day. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: Mara has 150 - 40 = <<150-40=110>>110 cards.<n>Janet has 110/2 = <<110/2=55>>55 cards since Mara has twice as many as Janet.<n>Brenda has 55 - 9 = <<55-9=46>>46 cards since Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda.<n>Therefore, they all have 110 + 55 + 46 = <<110+55+46=211>>211 cards.<n>So the final answer is 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. He rode the bus 20 blocks to the post office to get some stamps. Later, he came home the same way. How many blocks did Pete travel in all?<n>Output: The number of blocks traveled on the way to the post office was 5 + 20 = <<5+20=25>>25.<n>Pete traveled 25 × 2 = <<25*2=50>>50 blocks in all.<n>So the final answer is 50<n><n>Input: In a classroom, there are blue chairs, green chairs, and white chairs. There are 10 blue chairs. The green chairs are 3 times as many as the blue chairs, and there are 13 fewer white chairs than the green and blue chairs combined. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: There are 10 x 3 = <<10*3=30>>30 green chairs.<n>The total number of blue and green chairs is 10 + 30 = <<10+30=40>>40.<n>So, there are 40 - 13 = <<40-13=27>>27 white chairs.<n>Therefore, there are 40 +27 = <<40+27=67>>67 chairs in a classroom.<n>So the final answer is 67<n><n>Input: 4.5 gallons of coffee were divided among 18 thermoses. Genevieve drank 3 thermoses. How many pints of coffee did Genevieve drink?<n>Output: 4.5 gallons = 4.5 * 8 pints = <<4.5*8=36>>36 pints<n>36/18 = <<36/18=2>>2 pints<n>Genevieve drank 2*3=<<2*3=6>>6 pints of coffee.<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Alannah, Beatrix, and Queen are preparing for the new school year and have been given books by their parents. Alannah has 20 more books than Beatrix. Queen has 1/5 times more books than Alannah. If Beatrix has 30 books, how many books do the three have together?<n>Output: If Beatrix has 30 books, Alannah has 30 books + 20 books = <<30+20=50>>50 books.<n>Queen has 1/5 * 50 books = <<1/5*50=10>>10 more books than Alannah.<n>The total number of books Queen has is 50 books + 10 books = <<50+10=60>>60 books.<n>All three have 60 books + 50 books + 30 books = <<60+50+30=140>>140 books together<n>So the final answer is 140<n><n>Input: A bird eats 7 berries a day. Samuel has 5 birds. How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: Mara has 150 - 40 = <<150-40=110>>110 cards.<n>Janet has 110/2 = <<110/2=55>>55 cards since Mara has twice as many as Janet.<n>Brenda has 55 - 9 = <<55-9=46>>46 cards since Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda.<n>Therefore, they all have 110 + 55 + 46 = <<110+55+46=211>>211 cards.<n>So the final answer is 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. He rode the bus 20 blocks to the post office to get some stamps. Later, he came home the same way. How many blocks did Pete travel in all?<n>Output: The number of blocks traveled on the way to the post office was 5 + 20 = <<5+20=25>>25.<n>Pete traveled 25 × 2 = <<25*2=50>>50 blocks in all.<n>So the final answer is 50<n><n>Input: In a classroom, there are blue chairs, green chairs, and white chairs. There are 10 blue chairs. The green chairs are 3 times as many as the blue chairs, and there are 13 fewer white chairs than the green and blue chairs combined. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: There are 10 x 3 = <<10*3=30>>30 green chairs.<n>The total number of blue and green chairs is 10 + 30 = <<10+30=40>>40.<n>So, there are 40 - 13 = <<40-13=27>>27 white chairs.<n>Therefore, there are 40 +27 = <<40+27=67>>67 chairs in a classroom.<n>So the final answer is 67<n><n>Input: 4.5 gallons of coffee were divided among 18 thermoses. Genevieve drank 3 thermoses. How many pints of coffee did Genevieve drink?<n>Output: 4.5 gallons = 4.5 * 8 pints = <<4.5*8=36>>36 pints<n>36/18 = <<36/18=2>>2 pints<n>Genevieve drank 2*3=<<2*3=6>>6 pints of coffee.<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Alannah, Beatrix, and Queen are preparing for the new school year and have been given books by their parents. Alannah has 20 more books than Beatrix. Queen has 1/5 times more books than Alannah. If Beatrix has 30 books, how many books do the three have together?<n>Output: If Beatrix has 30 books, Alannah has 30 books + 20 books = <<30+20=50>>50 books.<n>Queen has 1/5 * 50 books = <<1/5*50=10>>10 more books than Alannah.<n>The total number of books Queen has is 50 books + 10 books = <<50+10=60>>60 books.<n>All three have 60 books + 50 books + 30 books = <<60+50+30=140>>140 books together<n>So the final answer is 140<n><n>Input: A bird eats 7 berries a day. Samuel has 5 birds. How many berries do Samuel's birds eat in 4 days?<n>Output: A bird eats 7 x 4 = <<7*4=28>>28 berries in 4 days.<n>So, 5 birds can eat 28 x 5 = <<28*5=140>>140 berries in 4 days.<n>So the final answer is 140<n><n>Input:Where would you put a folding chair if you do not plan to use it and you do not have any large doors in your house? Choices:  A: roof B: school C: beach D: closet E: garage<n>Output:		The correct answer is A: roof<n>

Choices:  A: shame B: arrest C: embarrassment D: go to jail E: tension<n>Output:		A: Choice is ashme<n>B: Choice is arrest<n>C: Choice is embarrassment<n>E: Choice is tension<n>So the final answer in this input is E<n><n>#! /bin/bash<n><n>for i in  {0..100}<n>do<n><n>      # Instruction: Please type in a number between 0 and 100:<n>      read num<n><n>      [[ $num >= 0 ]] && [[ $num <= 100 ]] || { echo "Enter a  number between 0 and <100"; exit 1; }<n><n>      # Instertion:Answer the following multiple-choice question.<n>      case $num in<n>          0 | 10 ) echo "The answer is "a" $num  ;;<n>          20 ) echo "The answe is "b" $num  ;;  <n>          40 ) echo "The Answer is "c" $num  ;; <n>          60 ) echo "The Answe is "d" $num  ;;                   <n>          80 ) echo "The Anwer is "e" $num ;; <n>          10 ) echo "Answer is "a" $Num  ;; <n>          20 ) Answer is "b" $Num ;; <n>          40 ) Answer is "c" ; echo "The answer is" $Num;; <n>          60) Answere is "d"; echo "The answer is E";; <n>          80 ) Answere is "E" $Num;; 20 ) Answer is a $Num ;; <n>      esac<n>      echo<n>done
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: Mara has 150 - 40 = <<150-40=110>>110 cards.<n>Janet has 110/2 = <<110/2=55>>55 cards since Mara has twice as many as Janet.<n>Brenda has 55 - 9 = <<55-9=46>>46 cards since Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda.<n>Therefore, they all have 110 + 55 + 46 = <<110+55+46=211>>211 cards.<n>So the final answer is 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. He rode the bus 20 blocks to the post office to get some stamps. Later, he came home the same way. How many blocks did Pete travel in all?<n>Output: The number of blocks traveled on the way to the post office was 5 + 20 = <<5+20=25>>25.<n>Pete traveled 25 × 2 = <<25*2=50>>50 blocks in all.<n>So the final answer is 50<n><n>Input: In a classroom, there are blue chairs, green chairs, and white chairs. There are 10 blue chairs. The green chairs are 3 times as many as the blue chairs, and there are 13 fewer white chairs than the green and blue chairs combined. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: There are 10 x 3 = <<10*3=30>>30 green chairs.<n>The total number of blue and green chairs is 10 + 30 = <<10+30=40>>40.<n>So, there are 40 - 13 = <<40-13=27>>27 white chairs.<n>Therefore, there are 40 +27 = <<40+27=67>>67 chairs in a classroom.<n>So the final answer is 67<n><n>Input: 4.5 gallons of coffee were divided among 18 thermoses. Genevieve drank 3 thermoses. How many pints of coffee did Genevieve drink?<n>Output: 4.5 gallons = 4.5 * 8 pints = <<4.5*8=36>>36 pints<n>36/18 = <<36/18=2>>2 pints<n>Genevieve drank 2*3=<<2*3=6>>6 pints of coffee.<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Alannah, Beatrix, and Queen are preparing for the new school year and have been given books by their parents. Alannah has 20 more books than Beatrix. Queen has 1/5 times more books than Alannah. If Beatrix has 30 books, how many books do the three have together?<n>Output: If Beatrix has 30 books, Alannah has 30 books + 20 books = <<30+20=50>>50 books.<n>Queen has 1/5 * 50 books = <<1/5*50=10>>10 more books than Alannah.<n>The total number of books Queen has is 50 books + 10 books = <<50+10=60>>60 books.<n>All three have 60 books + 50 books + 30 books = <<60+50+30=140>>140 books together<n>So the final answer is 140<n><n>Input: A bird eats 7 berries a day. Samuel has 5 birds. How many berries do Samuel's birds eat in 4 days?<n>Output: A bird eats 7 x 4 = <<7*4=28>>28 berries in 4 days.<n>So, 5 birds can eat 28 x 5 = <<28*5=140>>140 berries in 4 days.<n>So the final answer is 140<n><n>Input:What might a kid do with his friend before going to play? Choices:  A: laugh B: sit C: being entertained D: math E: meet<n>Output:		There are just 3 options.<n>1) Kid plays with you kid<n>2) Kid plays with you friend<n>3) Math problems<n>You can do nothing when a kid play with you friend.<n>

If a passenger riding the train on a trip walks 80 meters, how many seconds does it take her to finish the walk?<n>Output:12 m/s = 12 * 1s = <<12*1=12>>12 m/s<n>If A walk 80m in 1 second, then A walk A*(80/(12 m/s))s = <<80/(12* s)>=<<12*12=144>>144 seconds.<n>So the final answaer is 144<n><n>Input: What time was it when John ate dinner at 8:00? ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: Mara has 150 - 40 = <<150-40=110>>110 cards.<n>Janet has 110/2 = <<110/2=55>>55 cards since Mara has twice as many as Janet.<n>Brenda has 55 - 9 = <<55-9=46>>46 cards since Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda.<n>Therefore, they all have 110 + 55 + 46 = <<110+55+46=211>>211 cards.<n>So the final answer is 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. He rode the bus 20 blocks to the post office to get some stamps. Later, he came home the same way. How many blocks did Pete travel in all?<n>Output: The number of blocks traveled on the way to the post office was 5 + 20 = <<5+20=25>>25.<n>Pete traveled 25 × 2 = <<25*2=50>>50 blocks in all.<n>So the final answer is 50<n><n>Input: In a classroom, there are blue chairs, green chairs, and white chairs. There are 10 blue chairs. The green chairs are 3 times as many as the blue chairs, and there are 13 fewer white chairs than the green and blue chairs combined. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: There are 10 x 3 = <<10*3=30>>30 green chairs.<n>The total number of blue and green chairs is 10 + 30 = <<10+30=40>>40.<n>So, there are 40 - 13 = <<40-13=27>>27 white chairs.<n>Therefore, there are 40 +27 = <<40+27=67>>67 chairs in a classroom.<n>So the final answer is 67<n><n>Input: 4.5 gallons of coffee were divided among 18 thermoses. Genevieve drank 3 thermoses. Alannah has 20 more books than Beatrix. Queen has 1/5 times more books than Alannah. If Beatrix has 30 books, how many books do the three have together?<n>Output: If Beatrix has 30 books, Alannah has 30 books + 20 books = <<30+20=50>>50 books.<n>Queen has 1/5 * 50 books = <<1/5*50=10>>10 more books than Alannah.<n>The total number of books Queen has is 50 books + 10 books = <<50+10=60>>60 books.<n>All three have 60 books + 50 books + 30 books = <<60+50+30=140>>140 books together<n>So the final answer is 140<n><n>Input: A bird eats 7 berries a day. Alannah has 20 more books than Beatrix. Queen has 1/5 times more books than Alannah. If Beatrix has 30 books, how many books do the three have together?<n>Output: If Beatrix has 30 books, Alannah has 30 books + 20 books = <<30+20=50>>50 books.<n>Queen has 1/5 * 50 books = <<1/5*50=10>>10 more books than Alannah.<n>The total number of books Queen has is 50 books + 10 books = <<50+10=60>>60 books.<n>All three have 60 books + 50 books + 30 books = <<60+50+30=140>>140 books together<n>So the final answer is 140<n><n>Input: A bird eats 7 berries a day. Samuel has 5 birds. How many berries do Samuel's birds eat in 4 days?<n>Output: A bird eats 7 x 4 = <<7*4=28>>28 berries in 4 days.<n>So, 5 birds can eat 28 x 5 = <<28*5=140>>140 berries in 4 days.<n>So the final answer is 140<n><n>Input:What would happen to a person if his or her money is stolen? ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: Mara has 150 - 40 = <<150-40=110>>110 cards.<n>Janet has 110/2 = <<110/2=55>>55 cards since Mara has twice as many as Janet.<n>Brenda has 55 - 9 = <<55-9=46>>46 cards since Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda.<n>Therefore, they all have 110 + 55 + 46 = <<110+55+46=211>>211 cards.<n>So the final answer is 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. He rode the bus 20 blocks to the post office to get some stamps. Later, he came home the same way. How many blocks did Pete travel in all?<n>Output: The number of blocks traveled on the way to the post office was 5 + 20 = <<5+20=25>>25.<n>Pete traveled 25 × 2 = <<25*2=50>>50 blocks in all.<n>So the final answer is 50<n><n>Input: In a classroom, there are blue chairs, green chairs, and white chairs. There are 10 blue chairs. The green chairs are 3 times as many as the blue chairs, and there are 13 fewer white chairs than the green and blue chairs combined. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: There are 10 x 3 = <<10*3=30>>30 green chairs.<n>The total number of blue and green chairs is 10 + 30 = <<10+30=40>>40.<n>So, there are 40 - 13 = <<40-13=27>>27 white chairs.<n>Therefore, there are 40 +27 = <<40+27=67>>67 chairs in a classroom.<n>So the final answer is 67<n><n>Input: 4.5 gallons of coffee were divided among 18 thermoses. Genevieve drank 3 thermoses. How many pints of coffee did Genevieve drink?<n>Output: 4.5 gallons = 4.5 * 8 pints = <<4.5*8=36>>36 pints<n>36/18 = <<36/18=2>>2 pints<n>Genevieve drank 2*3=<<2*3=6>>6 pints of coffee.<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Alannah, Beatrix, and Queen are preparing for the new school year and have been given books by their parents. Alannah has 20 more books than Beatrix. Queen has 1/5 times more books than Alannah. If Beatrix has 30 books, how many books do the three have together?<n>Output: If Beatrix has 30 books, Alannah has 30 books + 20 books = <<30+20=50>>50 books.<n>Queen has 1/5 * 50 books = <<1/5*50=10>>10 more books than Alannah.<n>The total number of books Queen has is 50 books + 10 books = <<50+10=60>>60 books.<n>All three have 60 books + 50 books + 30 books = <<60+50+30=140>>140 books together<n>So the final answer is 140<n><n>Input: A bird eats 7 berries a day. Samuel has 5 birds. How many berries do Samuel's birds eat in 4 days?<n>Output: A bird eats 7 x 4 = <<7*4=28>>28 berries in 4 days.<n>So, 5 birds can eat 28 x 5 = <<28*5=140>>140 berries in 4 days.<n>So the final answer is 140<n><n>Input:Glass that hasn't been treated to be extra strong is what? Choices:  A: weak B: fragile C: forceless D: regular E: flimsy<n>Output:		The answer is B.<n>

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: Mara has 150 - 40 = <<150-40=110>>110 cards.<n>Janet has 110/2 = <<110/2=55>>55 cards since Mara has twice as many as Janet.<n>Brenda has 55 - 9 = <<55-9=46>>46 cards since Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda.<n>Therefore, they all have 110 + 55 + 46 = <<110+55+46=211>>211 cards.<n>So the final answer is 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. He rode the bus 20 blocks to the post office to get some stamps. Later, he came home the same way. How many blocks did Pete travel in all?<n>Output: The number of blocks traveled on the way to the post office was 5 + 20 = <<5+20=25>>25.<n>Pete traveled 25 × 2 = <<25*2=50>>50 blocks in all.<n>So the final answer is 50<n><n>Input: In a classroom, there are blue chairs, green chairs, and white chairs. There are 10 blue chairs. The green chairs are 3 times as many as the blue chairs, and there are 13 fewer white chairs than the green and blue chairs combined. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: There are 10 x 3 = <<10*3=30>>30 green chairs.<n>The total number of blue and green chairs is 10 + 30 = <<10+30=40>>40.<n>So, there are 40 - 13 = <<40-13=27>>27 white chairs.<n>Therefore, there are 40 +27 = <<40+27=67>>67 chairs in a classroom.<n>So the final answer is 67<n><n>Input: 4.5 gallons of coffee were divided among 18 thermoses. Genevieve drank 3 thermoses. How many pints of coffee did Genevieve drink?<n>Output: 4.5 gallons = 4.5 * 8 pints = <<4.5*8=36>>36 pints<n>36/18 = <<36/18=2>>2 pints<n>Genevieve drank 2*3=<<2*3=6>>6 pints of coffee.<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Alannah, Beatrix, and Queen are preparing for the new school year and have been given books by their parents. Alannah has 20 more books than Beatrix. Queen has 1/5 times more books than Alannah. If Beatrix has 30 books, how many books do the three have together?<n>Output: If Beatrix has 30 books, Alannah has 30 books + 20 books = <<30+20=50>>50 books.<n>Queen has 1/5 * 50 books = <<1/5*50=10>>10 more books than Alannah.<n>The total number of books Queen has is 50 books + 10 books = <<50+10=60>>60 books.<n>All three have 60 books + 50 books + 30 books = <<60+50+30=140>>140 books together<n>So the final answer is 140<n><n>Input: A bird eats 7 berries a day. Samuel has 5 birds. How many berries do Samuel's birds eat in 4 days?<n>Output: A bird eats 7 x 4 = <<7*4=28>>28 berries in 4 days.<n>So, 5 birds can eat 28 x 5 = <<28*5=140>>140 berries in 4 days.<n>So the final answer is 140<n><n>Input:If you were looking for a lemur where would you find it? Choices:  A: russia B: at home C: hole D: field E: heaven<n>Output:		The answer to this question is 'D'<n><n>Input:  You have 4 marbles. You want 2 more marbles. You have 3 colors of marbles. You have one type of marble in each color. If you only have orange marbles, how many marbles do you have in total?<n>Output: If you only have orange color then you take 4 + 2 = <?=?>4 marbles.<n>So there will be total 4 + 2+ 4 = 10 marbles<n>So the final answer 10<n><n><n>Input: A boy needs 38 more quarters than nickels to make a dollar. He has 44 quarters and 33 nickels. How many quarters does he have? <n>Output: A boy has 44 + 44 = 88 quarters.<n>He needs 38 more than 44 = 44 + (38+38) = 86 quarters.<n>Therefore, he has 88 quarters<n>So the final answer(answer choice) 88

Choices:  A: country club B: rich person's house C: pool D: park E: fitness center<n>Output:		Answer: C, park<n><n>Input:If three numbers are multiplied by 8, 2 remains the same and another becomes four more. Find the number.<n>Output:Let x,y,and z be the three numbers, then 8x+4y=1, 8(y-z)=6<n>Therefore 8x=1-(y-z), and 8x=1+y-z<n>Adding the equations, and combining like terms, we have 16x=(y+z)+y-z. Dividing both sides by 16 and multiplying by 4 we have 8x=4(y+z)+y+z-1<n>Dividing both sides by z, y+z can be omitted and we have 8x = 4y+4z+1<n>Adding the above equation and 1 we get 10x=4y+5z+3<n>Now comparing x terms we get x/3= (z+1)/5<n>Dividing both side by z+1, and simplifying we get x/2=z+1/5<n>Therefore, 2(z+1)=x+y+z<n>Adding 1 on the RH, and we get z+1+y+z=x+2<n>Comparing x terms again, we get x/1+y/1+z/1=2<n>Which simplifies to 2x=y+z.<n><n>And the equation simplifies to 4z=0, therefore z=0<n>Therefore the three numbers are three copies of 0.<n>Therefore, the three numbers are 0,0,0.<n>So the final answe is 0,0,&0<n><n><n>###### Solution<n>Input:Janet has 9 cards. Janet loses 8 cards in a game. Mara has 36 more cards than Janet. How does Janet's new number compare to Mara's new number?<n>Output:Janet has 19.<n><n>Input:There are 12 more apples than oranges in a box. A box of oranges costs 240 Rupees. How much does a box of apples cost?<n>Output:a box of apples costs 180 Rupees.<n><n>##### Tutorial

Choices:  A: top of home B: older houses C: victorian house D: own home E: material<n>Output:		<<E>>Material<n>A would be more common with victorian homes than older homes.<n>B would be more common with older homes than newer ones.<n>C would be more common with homes that are on the coast and in mountains than homes that are in the mid-west.<n>D would be more common with a home that you have lived at a long time than a new home.<n>Material homes can’t have a attic since they are all one floor.<n>So the final answers are D and E<n><n>Input: A city is going to run 3 marathons next year, one in April, one in July, and one in November. If each marathon has the same length and the same difficulty, what are the chances that next year, a marathon is held from February to May?<n>Output: In order to have a time of 36 hours, 46 minutes, 12 seconds, the fourth marathon runner must run over 35 miles in an hour less than the time for the first marathon runner.<n>So the runner must finish in 19 hours, 17 minutes, and 12 seconds in order to break the 13 hour, 57 minute, and 40 second record for running four marathons in a row.<n>From 19 hours 17 minutes 12 seconds till 4:30 pm, there have been 630 minutes, which is almost 10.5 hours. That means that the fourth runner was running the marathon at a pace of about 10.5 miles per hour.<n>Runners in the first and second marathons typically run at about 11 miles per hour, but this is in comparison to the pace of the people in third and fourth marathons who run at about 10.1mph <n>The fourth marathon runner must then run the first 20 miles of the race at a pace of 10.5mph in order to beat the marathon record by 2.5 miles.<n>That would imply that the first 8 marathons were run at approximately 11.5 mph, and then, the second 8 marathons are run at 10.5 mph

If Beatrix has 30 books, how many books do the three have together?<n>Output: If Beatrix has 30 books, Alannah has 30 books + 20 books = <<30+20=50>>50 books.<n>Queen has 1/5 * 50 books = <<1/5*50=10>>10 more books than Alannah.<n>The total number of books Queen has is 50 books + 10 books = <<50+10=60>>60 books.<n>All three have 60 books + 50 books + 30 books = <<60+50+30=140>>140 books together<n>So the final answer is 140<n><n>Input: A bird eats 7 berries a day. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: Mara has 150 - 40 = <<150-40=110>>110 cards.<n>Janet has 110/2 = <<110/2=55>>55 cards since Mara has twice as many as Janet.<n>Brenda has 55 - 9 = <<55-9=46>>46 cards since Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda.<n>Therefore, they all have 110 + 55 + 46 = <<110+55+46=211>>211 cards.<n>So the final answer is 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. He rode the bus 20 blocks to the post office to get some stamps. Later, he came home the same way. How many blocks did Pete travel in all?<n>Output: The number of blocks traveled on the way to the post office was 5 + 20 = <<5+20=25>>25.<n>Pete traveled 25 × 2 = <<25*2=50>>50 blocks in all.<n>So the final answer is 50<n><n>Input: In a classroom, there are blue chairs, green chairs, and white chairs. There are 10 blue chairs. The green chairs are 3 times as many as the blue chairs, and there are 13 fewer white chairs than the green and blue chairs combined. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: There are 10 x 3 = <<10*3=30>>30 green chairs.<n>The total number of blue and green chairs is 10 + 30 = <<10+30=40>>40.<n>So, there are 40 - 13 = <<40-13=27>>27 white chairs.<n>Therefore, there are 40 +27 = <<40+27=67>>67 chairs in a classroom.<n>So the final answer is 67<n><n>Input: 4.5 gallons of coffee were divided among 18 thermoses. Genevieve drank 3 thermoses. How much further did he run than the first 20 seconds?<n>Output:The first time Seth ran 54 m in 6 s.<n>The second time Seth ran 31 more m in 20s.<n>=><n>The third run Seth ran 32 m in 20 s.<n>The fourth time Seth's m = 54 -32/6 = <<54-32/6=18.5>>18.5 m,<n>The fifth time Seth ran 18.5 more m in 24 s.<n>The sixth time Seth ran 24 more m in 30 s.<n>The seventh time Seth run 30/6 = <<30/6=5>>5 m.<n>Therefore, Seth runs 18.5 + 3 + 5 = <<18.5+3+5=26>>26 more m.<n>So the final Answer is 26<n><n>Input: In the classroom, there are 3 red crayons and 6 green crayons and 5 yellow crayons. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: Mara has 150 - 40 = <<150-40=110>>110 cards.<n>Janet has 110/2 = <<110/2=55>>55 cards since Mara has twice as many as Janet.<n>Brenda has 55 - 9 = <<55-9=46>>46 cards since Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda.<n>Therefore, they all have 110 + 55 + 46 = <<110+55+46=211>>211 cards.<n>So the final answer is 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. He rode the bus 20 blocks to the post office to get some stamps. Later, he came home the same way. How many blocks did Pete travel in all?<n>Output: The number of blocks traveled on the way to the post office was 5 + 20 = <<5+20=25>>25.<n>Pete traveled 25 × 2 = <<25*2=50>>50 blocks in all.<n>So the final answer is 50<n><n>Input: In a classroom, there are blue chairs, green chairs, and white chairs. There are 10 blue chairs. The green chairs are 3 times as many as the blue chairs, and there are 13 fewer white chairs than the green and blue chairs combined. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: There are 10 x 3 = <<10*3=30>>30 green chairs.<n>The total number of blue and green chairs is 10 + 30 = <<10+30=40>>40.<n>So, there are 40 - 13 = <<40-13=27>>27 white chairs.<n>Therefore, there are 40 +27 = <<40+27=67>>67 chairs in a classroom.<n>So the final answer is 67<n><n>Input: 4.5 gallons of coffee were divided among 18 thermoses. If the total area of the three rectangular objects is 26 square feet and the table takes up one-fourth of the remaining space, how many square feet of space is between the table and the bench?<n>Output: Lets say: T = table W = width of table B = bench<n>T = 1/4 * (36 - (T + B))<n>T = (36 - (36 - B - W))<n>T = 36 - (B + W)<n>T <= 36<n>B + W <= 36 - 36<n>B+W <= 0<n>B <= 0 (Since B is greater than 0, B cannot exceed zero.)<n>Therefore, there is no space between the table and the  bench.<n>So the final  answer is 0<n><n>Input: Sam has 20 coins. The odds of getting a particular number are 1 in 6.<n><n>#5: In American football, three points are awarded for a touchdown and one point for a field goal. Choices: no score<n>      C: 1 D: 2 E: 3 F: 4 G: 5<n>Output: The score is three in total, so the answer is D.<n><n>#6: "X" indicates that the value in X is 5. Choices: 0<n>      C: 3 D:9 E: 8<n>Output: Each letter's position in the alphabet has seven positions, so the answer is:<n><n>#7: If a number of notes is equal to a musical staff
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: Mara has 150 - 40 = <<150-40=110>>110 cards.<n>Janet has 110/2 = <<110/2=55>>55 cards since Mara has twice as many as Janet.<n>Brenda has 55 - 9 = <<55-9=46>>46 cards since Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda.<n>Therefore, they all have 110 + 55 + 46 = <<110+55+46=211>>211 cards.<n>So the final answer is 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. He rode the bus 20 blocks to the post office to get some stamps. Later, he came home the same way. How many blocks did Pete travel in all?<n>Output: The number of blocks traveled on the way to the post office was 5 + 20 = <<5+20=25>>25.<n>Pete traveled 25 × 2 = <<25*2=50>>50 blocks in all.<n>So the final answer is 50<n><n>Input: In a classroom, there are blue chairs, green chairs, and white chairs. There are 10 blue chairs. The green chairs are 3 times as many as the blue chairs, and there are 13 fewer white chairs than the green and blue chairs combined. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: There are 10 x 3 = <<10*3=30>>30 green chairs.<n>The total number of blue and green chairs is 10 + 30 = <<10+30=40>>40.<n>So, there are 40 - 13 = <<40-13=27>>27 white chairs.<n>Therefore, there are 40 +27 = <<40+27=67>>67 chairs in a classroom.<n>So the final answer is 67<n><n>Input: 4.5 gallons of coffee were divided among 18 thermoses. Genevieve drank 3 thermoses. How many pints of coffee did Genevieve drink?<n>Output: 4.5 gallons = 4.5 * 8 pints = <<4.5*8=36>>36 pints<n>36/18 = <<36/18=2>>2 pints<n>Genevieve drank 2*3=<<2*3=6>>6 pints of coffee.<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Alannah, Beatrix, and Queen are preparing for the new school year and have been given books by their parents. Alannah has 20 more books than Beatrix. Queen has 1/5 times more books than Alannah. If Beatrix has 30 books, how many books do the three have together?<n>Output: If Beatrix has 30 books, Alannah has 30 books + 20 books = <<30+20=50>>50 books.<n>Queen has 1/5 * 50 books = <<1/5*50=10>>10 more books than Alannah.<n>The total number of books Queen has is 50 books + 10 books = <<50+10=60>>60 books.<n>All three have 60 books + 50 books + 30 books = <<60+50+30=140>>140 books together<n>So the final answer is 140<n><n>Input: A bird eats 7 berries a day. Samuel has 5 birds. How many berries do Samuel's birds eat in 4 days?<n>Output: A bird eats 7 x 4 = <<7*4=28>>28 berries in 4 days.<n>So, 5 birds can eat 28 x 5 = <<28*5=140>>140 berries in 4 days.<n>So the final answer is 140<n><n>Input:Where would you go if you didn't feel like baking a cake yourself? Choices:  A: theater B: refrigerator C: bakery D: grocery store E: oven<n>Output:		You go to the theatre.<n>Input:Who would you want to attend a concert with? Choices: 1. Brother 2. Sister 3. Dad 4. Mom 5. Grandmother 6. Aunt 7. Uncle 8. Girlfriend 9. Boyfriend 10. All of them<n>Output: You attend the concert with your girlfriend.<n>Input:What is the best way to spend a Saturday afternoon? Choices:  C: Watching a movie B: Playing video games A: Biking D: Gardening E: Cleaning the house F: Walking the dog G: Doing chores<n>Output: You enjoy watching a movie and playing video games best.<n>Input: What is a good way to spend a Sunday afternoon? There is no such thing as an octagon, because an octagon has six sides, but its name has no meaning to an octagon: An octagon is a geometrical enclosure of eight triangles, or eight isosceles triangles.<n><n>Input: A mother gave her children each 90 nickels and 45 dimes for a total of 150 coins. Choices:  B: 5 C: 3 D: 9 E: 2 F : 4<n>Output:C: 3<n>Answer:The mom told each of her children the same amount of coins, so 150/3 = <<150/3=50>>5 = 3.<n><n>Input: 1/2 of the class is boys, and 1/7 of the class is girls. If there are 12 girls in the class, how many boys are in the class? Choices:  F: 2 G: 4 H: 6 I: 7 J: 5<n>Output:G: 4<n>Answer:{12*(1/2/17)} = 4/9 = 1/3 = 4/3 = 4 girls<n><n>Input:Which line does NOT belong to a family? Choices: F: The blue one below G: The yellow line below H: The red line below I: The brown line below J
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: Mara has 150 - 40 = <<150-40=110>>110 cards.<n>Janet has 110/2 = <<110/2=55>>55 cards since Mara has twice as many as Janet.<n>Brenda has 55 - 9 = <<55-9=46>>46 cards since Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda.<n>Therefore, they all have 110 + 55 + 46 = <<110+55+46=211>>211 cards.<n>So the final answer is 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. He rode the bus 20 blocks to the post office to get some stamps. Later, he came home the same way. How many blocks did Pete travel in all?<n>Output: The number of blocks traveled on the way to the post office was 5 + 20 = <<5+20=25>>25.<n>Pete traveled 25 × 2 = <<25*2=50>>50 blocks in all.<n>So the final answer is 50<n><n>Input: In a classroom, there are blue chairs, green chairs, and white chairs. There are 10 blue chairs. The green chairs are 3 times as many as the blue chairs, and there are 13 fewer white chairs than the green and blue chairs combined. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: There are 10 x 3 = <<10*3=30>>30 green chairs.<n>The total number of blue and green chairs is 10 + 30 = <<10+30=40>>40.<n>So, there are 40 - 13 = <<40-13=27>>27 white chairs.<n>Therefore, there are 40 +27 = <<40+27=67>>67 chairs in a classroom.<n>So the final answer is 67<n><n>Input: 4.5 gallons of coffee were divided among 18 thermoses. Genevieve drank 3 thermoses. How many pints of coffee did Genevieve drink?<n>Output: 4.5 gallons = 4.5 * 8 pints = <<4.5*8=36>>36 pints<n>36/18 = <<36/18=2>>2 pints<n>Genevieve drank 2*3=<<2*3=6>>6 pints of coffee.<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Alannah, Beatrix, and Queen are preparing for the new school year and have been given books by their parents. Alannah has 20 more books than Beatrix. Queen has 1/5 times more books than Alannah. If Beatrix has 30 books, how many books do the three have together?<n>Output: If Beatrix has 30 books, Alannah has 30 books + 20 books = <<30+20=50>>50 books.<n>Queen has 1/5 * 50 books = <<1/5*50=10>>10 more books than Alannah.<n>The total number of books Queen has is 50 books + 10 books = <<50+10=60>>60 books.<n>All three have 60 books + 50 books + 30 books = <<60+50+30=140>>140 books together<n>So the final answer is 140<n><n>Input: A bird eats 7 berries a day. Samuel has 5 birds. How many berries do Samuel's birds eat in 4 days?<n>Output: A bird eats 7 x 4 = <<7*4=28>>28 berries in 4 days.<n>So, 5 birds can eat 28 x 5 = <<28*5=140>>140 berries in 4 days.<n>So the final answer is 140<n><n>Input:The parents thought their children should learn teamwork, what were they signed up for? Choices:  A: throw things B: play sports C: play games D: play ball E: play chess<n>Output:		The answers are D throw things and A play ball.<n>So the final answers are A and D<n><n>Input: Which is larger? 5 cups of milk or 3/5 cup of milk?<n>Output:3/5 cup of Milk= <<3/5cup=2/5>>1/5 cups<n>Therefore 5 cup-1/5 cup = <<5cup=2>>2 cups of milk.<n>Milk is larger than the cup of milk.<n>So the final ansswer is 5<n><n>input: 5 times 2 =<<5*2=10>>1. 1+1 =<<1+1=2>>2. 2 times 2 =<<2*2=4>>. 4 + 2 =<<4+2=6>>. 6 + 2 =<<6+2=8>>. 10 + 2 =<<10+2=12>>. 12 + 2 =<<8+2=10>>.

If Beatrix has 30 books, how many books do the three have together?<n>Output: If Beatrix has 30 books, Alannah has 30 books + 20 books = <<30+20=50>>50 books.<n>Queen has 1/5 * 50 books = <<1/5*50=10>>10 more books than Alannah.<n>The total number of books Queen has is 50 books + 10 books = <<50+10=60>>60 books.<n>All three have 60 books + 50 books + 30 books = <<60+50+30=140>>140 books together<n>So the final answer is 140<n><n>Input: A bird eats 7 berries a day. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: Mara has 150 - 40 = <<150-40=110>>110 cards.<n>Janet has 110/2 = <<110/2=55>>55 cards since Mara has twice as many as Janet.<n>Brenda has 55 - 9 = <<55-9=46>>46 cards since Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda.<n>Therefore, they all have 110 + 55 + 46 = <<110+55+46=211>>211 cards.<n>So the final answer is 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. He rode the bus 20 blocks to the post office to get some stamps. Later, he came home the same way. How many blocks did Pete travel in all?<n>Output: The number of blocks traveled on the way to the post office was 5 + 20 = <<5+20=25>>25.<n>Pete traveled 25 × 2 = <<25*2=50>>50 blocks in all.<n>So the final answer is 50<n><n>Input: In a classroom, there are blue chairs, green chairs, and white chairs. How many berries do Samuel's birds eat in 4 days?<n>Output: A bird eats 7 x 4 = <<7*4=28>>28 berries in 4 days.<n>So, 5 birds can eat 28 x 5 = <<28*5=140>>140 berries in 4 days.<n>So the final answer is 140<n><n>Input:Someone who is awake is likely to know what's going on because they are this? Choices:  A: alert B: deep sleep C: drink coffee D: open eyes E: conscious<n>Output:		In order to know what's happening, someone who is awake needs to be both alert and conscious.<n><n>Input: 7 + 7 = _______<n>Output:7 + 7 = + 14<n><n>Input: Which of these letters comes before the letter "k"?A: B C:D E: F G: H _________?<n>Output: Choosing the right answer in this context means answering "F", because the letter "k" occurs after "H" when placed in the alphabetic sequence.<n><n>Input: If a triangle has sides of 18, 20, and 7, which of these is the value of the angle of the triangle? Choices: A: 90 degrees B: 45 degrees C: 25 degrees D: 10 degrees<n>Output: If the triangle has a side of 7 degrees, the angle is 105 degrees.<n><n>Input:The area of the large square is 42cm2.What is the area of the small square?A:84 B:104 C:124 D:96<n>Output: If the large square is 8cmx8cm, the small square is 4cm x 4cm and has half its area.<n><n>Input: In the word "MOM," what comes second?A: M B: O C: E D: None<n>Output: The second letter in the word "MOM" is "O."<n><n>Input: What happens when you add 50 and 60?A: 130 B: 110 C: 90 D: 99<n>Output: 50 + 60 = 110<n><n>Input: The number 7 squared is 49. Which of these must be greater than 7? Choices: A> B> C> D> A<n>Output: When 49 is greater than 7, 7 squared is not 49. 7squared is 382<n><n>Input: In which of these months does January come first? Choices: A)June B)March C)April D)None<n>Output: January comes first because the other months come after it in the list.<n><n>Input: Which one doesn't belong in this sequence? Choices: A. 1
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: Mara has 150 - 40 = <<150-40=110>>110 cards.<n>Janet has 110/2 = <<110/2=55>>55 cards since Mara has twice as many as Janet.<n>Brenda has 55 - 9 = <<55-9=46>>46 cards since Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda.<n>Therefore, they all have 110 + 55 + 46 = <<110+55+46=211>>211 cards.<n>So the final answer is 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. He rode the bus 20 blocks to the post office to get some stamps. Later, he came home the same way. How many blocks did Pete travel in all?<n>Output: The number of blocks traveled on the way to the post office was 5 + 20 = <<5+20=25>>25.<n>Pete traveled 25 × 2 = <<25*2=50>>50 blocks in all.<n>So the final answer is 50<n><n>Input: In a classroom, there are blue chairs, green chairs, and white chairs. There are 10 blue chairs. The green chairs are 3 times as many as the blue chairs, and there are 13 fewer white chairs than the green and blue chairs combined. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: There are 10 x 3 = <<10*3=30>>30 green chairs.<n>The total number of blue and green chairs is 10 + 30 = <<10+30=40>>40.<n>So, there are 40 - 13 = <<40-13=27>>27 white chairs.<n>Therefore, there are 40 +27 = <<40+27=67>>67 chairs in a classroom.<n>So the final answer is 67<n><n>Input: 4.5 gallons of coffee were divided among 18 thermoses. Genevieve drank 3 thermoses. How many pints of coffee did Genevieve drink?<n>Output: 4.5 gallons = 4.5 * 8 pints = <<4.5*8=36>>36 pints<n>36/18 = <<36/18=2>>2 pints<n>Genevieve drank 2*3=<<2*3=6>>6 pints of coffee.<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Alannah, Beatrix, and Queen are preparing for the new school year and have been given books by their parents. Alannah has 20 more books than Beatrix. Queen has 1/5 times more books than Alannah. If Beatrix has 30 books, how many books do the three have together?<n>Output: If Beatrix has 30 books, Alannah has 30 books + 20 books = <<30+20=50>>50 books.<n>Queen has 1/5 * 50 books = <<1/5*50=10>>10 more books than Alannah.<n>The total number of books Queen has is 50 books + 10 books = <<50+10=60>>60 books.<n>All three have 60 books + 50 books + 30 books = <<60+50+30=140>>140 books together<n>So the final answer is 140<n><n>Input: A bird eats 7 berries a day. Samuel has 5 birds. How many berries do Samuel's birds eat in 4 days?<n>Output: A bird eats 7 x 4 = <<7*4=28>>28 berries in 4 days.<n>So, 5 birds can eat 28 x 5 = <<28*5=140>>140 berries in 4 days.<n>So the final answer is 140<n><n>Input:What do humans do when in a race? Choices:  A: lay eggs B: eat fruit C: wrestle D: compete with each other E: draw pictures<n>Output:		The correct answer is "E", which can be inferred by the question and is not even mentioned in the choices.<n>

There are three questions.<n><n>Input: The average high temperature in July is 93 degrees. For every 5 degrees above the normal high temperature, it rains 25% of the time. For every 10 degrees above the normal high, it rains 50% of the time. If the average low is 70 degrees, what is the probability that it will rain on any given day in July?<n>Output: Average temperature range = <15(43 degrees)> = <<15*43=655>>655 degrees above normal.<n><n>Rain probability when average high is 10 degrees above normal = 50%/10 degrees = <<50/10=50>> 50%.<n>Rain probability when above temperature is 5 degrees above normal = <<25/7(115 degrees)-(5-10)=12>> 50%<n>Probability when above temperature is 655 degrees from normal = <<50+(25*655)/10655-50=34>> 34%.<n>Therefore, it rains 34% of the days in July.<n>So the final result is 34%<n>
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: Mara has 150 - 40 = <<150-40=110>>110 cards.<n>Janet has 110/2 = <<110/2=55>>55 cards since Mara has twice as many as Janet.<n>Brenda has 55 - 9 = <<55-9=46>>46 cards since Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda.<n>Therefore, they all have 110 + 55 + 46 = <<110+55+46=211>>211 cards.<n>So the final answer is 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: There are 10 x 3 = <<10*3=30>>30 green chairs.<n>The total number of blue and green chairs is 10 + 30 = <<10+30=40>>40.<n>So, there are 40 - 13 = <<40-13=27>>27 white chairs.<n>Therefore, there are 40 +27 = <<40+27=67>>67 chairs in a classroom.<n>So the final answer is 67<n><n>Input: 4.5 gallons of coffee were divided among 18 thermoses. Choices:  A: mouth B: can C: human D: snake E: kentucky fried chicken<n>Output:		LET'S START BY IDENTIFYING WHAT BELONGS TO EACH MAJOR CATEGORY. Choice A: <<mouth>>mouth is a mouth part. Therefore, answer A is wrong.<n>Choice B: <<can>>can is a body part. Choice C: <<human>>human is a living thing. Choice D: <<snake>>snake is NOT a living thing. Choices E: <<Kentucky Fried Chicken>>Kentucky Fried Chickens are not animals.<n>So the final choice is LIVING THING<n><n>Input: 1-2 4-4 A: A B: B<n>Output: 1<n><n><n><n>---<n><n>### Section: 4.2 Problem Solving<n><n>---<n><n>## Section: 4.3 Problem Solving with Conditional Statements   ### Instruction:Answer each question with YES or NO.<n><n>**Directions:** Decide whether the statement is true or false.<n><n><n>**NOTE:** You MUST write YES or NO for your answer.<n><n>**1.** if m < 20, then (−14 + 3)/12 = 2.4<n><n>**2.** if w > 4, then (−11)/21 = 0.5238094948<n><n>**3.** if h > 15, then (−18 − 5)/26 = 98.269230769<n><n>**4.** if u < −12, then 2(12 + 5) + u = −15<n><n>**0.** if j > −2, then 2j − 5 = −125 + 15<n><n>**6.** if t = 4, then 6.4m − 2m = 0<n><n>**7.** if q > −8, then 12.15 – 3q = 15.85<n><n>**8.** if h > −10, then 2.3x − 2 = −3<n><n>**9.** if i > −2, then –i + 3 = −1<n><n>*
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: Mara has 150 - 40 = <<150-40=110>>110 cards.<n>Janet has 110/2 = <<110/2=55>>55 cards since Mara has twice as many as Janet.<n>Brenda has 55 - 9 = <<55-9=46>>46 cards since Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda.<n>Therefore, they all have 110 + 55 + 46 = <<110+55+46=211>>211 cards.<n>So the final answer is 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. He rode the bus 20 blocks to the post office to get some stamps. Later, he came home the same way. How many blocks did Pete travel in all?<n>Output: The number of blocks traveled on the way to the post office was 5 + 20 = <<5+20=25>>25.<n>Pete traveled 25 × 2 = <<25*2=50>>50 blocks in all.<n>So the final answer is 50<n><n>Input: In a classroom, there are blue chairs, green chairs, and white chairs. There are 10 blue chairs. The green chairs are 3 times as many as the blue chairs, and there are 13 fewer white chairs than the green and blue chairs combined. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: There are 10 x 3 = <<10*3=30>>30 green chairs.<n>The total number of blue and green chairs is 10 + 30 = <<10+30=40>>40.<n>So, there are 40 - 13 = <<40-13=27>>27 white chairs.<n>Therefore, there are 40 +27 = <<40+27=67>>67 chairs in a classroom.<n>So the final answer is 67<n><n>Input: 4.5 gallons of coffee were divided among 18 thermoses. Genevieve drank 3 thermoses. How many pints of coffee did Genevieve drink?<n>Output: 4.5 gallons = 4.5 * 8 pints = <<4.5*8=36>>36 pints<n>36/18 = <<36/18=2>>2 pints<n>Genevieve drank 2*3=<<2*3=6>>6 pints of coffee.<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Alannah, Beatrix, and Queen are preparing for the new school year and have been given books by their parents. Alannah has 20 more books than Beatrix. Queen has 1/5 times more books than Alannah. If Beatrix has 30 books, how many books do the three have together?<n>Output: If Beatrix has 30 books, Alannah has 30 books + 20 books = <<30+20=50>>50 books.<n>Queen has 1/5 * 50 books = <<1/5*50=10>>10 more books than Alannah.<n>The total number of books Queen has is 50 books + 10 books = <<50+10=60>>60 books.<n>All three have 60 books + 50 books + 30 books = <<60+50+30=140>>140 books together<n>So the final answer is 140<n><n>Input: A bird eats 7 berries a day. Samuel has 5 birds. How many berries do Samuel's birds eat in 4 days?<n>Output: A bird eats 7 x 4 = <<7*4=28>>28 berries in 4 days.<n>So, 5 birds can eat 28 x 5 = <<28*5=140>>140 berries in 4 days.<n>So the final answer is 140<n><n>Input:If they were celebrating the occasion, how could the occasion be described? Choices:  A: drinking B: intimacy C: dancing D: happiness E: enjoyment<n>Output:		The occasion could be described as dancing<n>So the final answer if dancing<n><n>Input:  What did Jack intend to show at his stand? <Choices: A: two oranges B: five oranges C: six lemons D: three pears E: a pear<n>Output: Jack intended to show two lemons<n>So the final answer lemons<n><n>Input: Jack showed two lemons at his stand. How many lemons did he show? <Choices:  A: two B: nine<n><n>Output: The number 2 lemons<n>Solution:Jack did not show the number 2 lemon.<n>So the final answare: 0<n><n>Input:  If we call the number 935302 our area code, what would be the largest city in our state? <choices: A: Dallas B: Austin C: Houston D: El Paso E: McAllen<n>Output: We cannot determine the number of the answer<n>So the final answer: Not Available<n><n>Input:  Suppose a large number of people attend a sporting event, and all of them are in the upper half of the audience. What should be said about the number of people in the upper half? <Choices: The answer should be larger than five<n><n>Output: It is impossible to determine how many people are in the upper half.<n>So the final answers: 0<n><n>input:  The number of people in the lower half is three times the number of people in upper half<n>Output: The number in lower half is three times larger, so 3 times 5 = 15<n>So the final answer in lower half is 15<n><n>## Next<n><n>### Question<n><n>If they were celebrating, how could the occasion have been described?<n><n>#### Answer code<n><n><img src="https://github.com/programiz/programiz-docs/blob/master/videos/practice/instructions/Instructions-v5-2.jpg" /><n><n>### Answer<n><n>a) dancing with one another<n><n>#### Challenge<n><n>Input: Which option describes the occasion that could have been described?<n>Output: dancing with one another

Choices:  A: cabinet B: computer printer C: suitcase D: office supply store E: artist's studio<n>Output:		You can find large pieces of paper not for sale in E: artist’s studio.<n>Answer option Choices:<n> A: cabinet -> There is no mention of the size of a paper here. So, option A is invalid<n> B: computer printer -> Computer printers are not big enough for us to get large pieces of paper from. So, option B is invalid<n> C: suitcase -> Not for sale means you cannot buy this. So, option C is invalid<n> D: office supply store -> Office supplies like pen, scissors, notebook, etc. are for sale. So, option D is invalid<n> E: artist's studios -> Artists always use some large sheets of papers when they paint or draw. So, option E is correct<n>So the final answer choice is E: artist's’ studio<n><n>Input: The ratio of birds to dogs in a yard is 4:3. Choose 4 different dogs that have fewer than 4 birds each.<n>Output: To find the sum of the birds and dog, we need to find the ratio of dogs to birds since dogs and birds have the same number of members.<n>Dogs = dogs/birds x dogs/birds<n>birds = dogs/birds/birds<n>bird = birds/birds/bird = dogs/birds<n>Thus, the sum of dogs + birds = birds + dogs = dogs + dogs + birds + birds<n>So the final answer sum is 6<n><n><n>---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------<n>### Part 2: Solve each of the three following problems using basic arithmetic operations.<n>Each problem has an input and an output. He rode the bus 20 blocks to the post office to get some stamps. Later, he came home the same way. How many blocks did Pete travel in all?<n>Output: The number of blocks traveled on the way to the post office was 5 + 20 = <<5+20=25>>25.<n>Pete traveled 25 × 2 = <<25*2=50>>50 blocks in all.<n>So the final answer is 50<n><n>Input: In a classroom, there are blue chairs, green chairs, and white chairs. There are 10 blue chairs. The green chairs are 3 times as many as the blue chairs, and there are 13 fewer white chairs than the green and blue chairs combined. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: There are 10 x 3 = <<10*3=30>>30 green chairs.<n>The total number of blue and green chairs is 10 + 30 = <<10+30=40>>40.<n>So, there are 40 - 13 = <<40-13=27>>27 white chairs.<n>Therefore, there are 40 +27 = <<40+27=67>>67 chairs in a classroom.<n>So the final answer is 67<n><n>Input: 4.5 gallons of coffee were divided among 18 thermoses. Genevieve drank 3 thermoses. How many pints of coffee did Genevieve drink?<n>Output: 4.5 gallons = 4.5 * 8 pints = <<4.5*8=36>>36 pints<n>36/18 = <<36/18=2>>2 pints<n>Genevieve drank 2*3=<<2*3=6>>6 pints of coffee.<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Alannah, Beatrix, and Queen are preparing for the new school year and have been given books by their parents. Alannah has 20 more books than Beatrix. Queen has 1/5 times more books than Alannah. If Beatrix has 30 books, how many books do the three have together?<n>Output: If Beatrix has 30 books, Alannah has 30 books + 20 books = <<30+20=50>>50 books.<n>Queen has 1/5 * 50 books = <<1/5*50=10>>10 more books than Alannah.<n>The total number of books Queen has is 50 books + 10 books = <<50+10=60>>60 books.<n>All three have 60 books + 50 books + 30 books = <<60+50+30=140>>140 books together<n>So the final answer is 140<n><n>Input: A bird eats 7 berries a day. Samuel has 5 birds. How many berries do Samuel's birds eat in 4 days?<n>Output: A bird eats 7 x 4 = <<7*4=28>>28 berries in 4 days.<n>So, 5 birds can eat 28 x 5 = <<28*5=140>>140 berries in 4 days.<n>So the final answer is 140<n><n>Input:What is not a safe way to transport jewelry on vacation? Choices:  A: suitcase B: department store C: safe deposit box D: these twos are not safe way to transport jewellery E: lady's boudoir<n>Output:		A is a right answer because a suitcase gets lost very easily and jewelry is the most valuable thing.<n>
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: Mara has 150 - 40 = <<150-40=110>>110 cards.<n>Janet has 110/2 = <<110/2=55>>55 cards since Mara has twice as many as Janet.<n>Brenda has 55 - 9 = <<55-9=46>>46 cards since Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda.<n>Therefore, they all have 110 + 55 + 46 = <<110+55+46=211>>211 cards.<n>So the final answer is 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: Mara has 150 - 40 = <<150-40=110>>110 cards.<n>Janet has 110/2 = <<110/2=55>>55 cards since Mara has twice as many as Janet.<n>Brenda has 55 - 9 = <<55-9=46>>46 cards since Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda.<n>Therefore, they all have 110 + 55 + 46 = <<110+55+46=211>>211 cards.<n>So the final answer is 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. And a cowboy riding West is 175 miles / 20 miles per day.<n>Hence, 40 days from going East and 20 days from going west, he rides 40 + 20 = 60 miles back to where he started from.<n>Hence the Answer is the starting point<n><n>Input: A chicken has seven brothers. Each one of its brothers lays an egg every day. How many eggs do they lay in one week?<n>Output: A chicken has 1 egg every day. Hence, it lays 7 eggs in a week. Also, each brother lays 1 egg every day, hence 7 brothers lay 7 eggs in a day which is 7*7 = 49 eggs every day. This results in 49 eggs * 7 (days in a week) = 333 eggs in a week.<n><n>Input: A farmer plants his seeds in a garden. In each row, there are 80 seeds planted. Thus, his seeds are separated into 5 equal subgroups, which have 80 seeds each.

Choices:  A: original B: old C: coke clear D: former E: familiar<n>Output:		After new coke was discontinue the formula is E since it the same<n><n>Input: How many miles are there between Philadelphia and Washington DC?  <5,0,False,True>6</5,0,False,,True><n>Output: There are <<5+6=11>>11 miles between Philadelphia and Washington, DC.<n>So the final Answer is 11 Miles<n><n>Input: Jane can mow a lawn in two hours less than her cousin, Julie. How many lawns can Jane mow in one day?  <2,0,False,False>7</2,0,False,,False><n>Output: If Jane can mow a yard in 2 hours, she can mow 2 hours * 5 = <<2*5=10>>1 lawns in one day.<n>Jane takes <<2 * 10 = 20>>20 hours less than Julie to mow the same number of lawns. Therefore, <<2*10-20=2>>2 lawns in one da<n>So the final Answer 2 Lianas<n>
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: Mara has 150 - 40 = <<150-40=110>>110 cards.<n>Janet has 110/2 = <<110/2=55>>55 cards since Mara has twice as many as Janet.<n>Brenda has 55 - 9 = <<55-9=46>>46 cards since Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda.<n>Therefore, they all have 110 + 55 + 46 = <<110+55+46=211>>211 cards.<n>So the final answer is 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. He rode the bus 20 blocks to the post office to get some stamps. Later, he came home the same way. How many blocks did Pete travel in all?<n>Output: The number of blocks traveled on the way to the post office was 5 + 20 = <<5+20=25>>25.<n>Pete traveled 25 × 2 = <<25*2=50>>50 blocks in all.<n>So the final answer is 50<n><n>Input: In a classroom, there are blue chairs, green chairs, and white chairs. There are 10 blue chairs. The green chairs are 3 times as many as the blue chairs, and there are 13 fewer white chairs than the green and blue chairs combined. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: There are 10 x 3 = <<10*3=30>>30 green chairs.<n>The total number of blue and green chairs is 10 + 30 = <<10+30=40>>40.<n>So, there are 40 - 13 = <<40-13=27>>27 white chairs.<n>Therefore, there are 40 +27 = <<40+27=67>>67 chairs in a classroom.<n>So the final answer is 67<n><n>Input: 4.5 gallons of coffee were divided among 18 thermoses. Genevieve drank 3 thermoses. How many pints of coffee did Genevieve drink?<n>Output: 4.5 gallons = 4.5 * 8 pints = <<4.5*8=36>>36 pints<n>36/18 = <<36/18=2>>2 pints<n>Genevieve drank 2*3=<<2*3=6>>6 pints of coffee.<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Alannah, Beatrix, and Queen are preparing for the new school year and have been given books by their parents. Alannah has 20 more books than Beatrix. Queen has 1/5 times more books than Alannah. If Beatrix has 30 books, how many books do the three have together?<n>Output: If Beatrix has 30 books, Alannah has 30 books + 20 books = <<30+20=50>>50 books.<n>Queen has 1/5 * 50 books = <<1/5*50=10>>10 more books than Alannah.<n>The total number of books Queen has is 50 books + 10 books = <<50+10=60>>60 books.<n>All three have 60 books + 50 books + 30 books = <<60+50+30=140>>140 books together<n>So the final answer is 140<n><n>Input: A bird eats 7 berries a day. Samuel has 5 birds. How many berries do Samuel's birds eat in 4 days?<n>Output: A bird eats 7 x 4 = <<7*4=28>>28 berries in 4 days.<n>So, 5 birds can eat 28 x 5 = <<28*5=140>>140 berries in 4 days.<n>So the final answer is 140<n><n>Input:Someone who doesn't care about about someone else and wishes them to fail has what feeling towards them? Choices:  A: unfeeling B: negligence C: antipathy D: indifferent E: rapport<n>Output:		The answer is B: negligence<n><n>Input: In the following set of sentences, underline the punctuation, and choose the correct option given in brackets:<n><n> 1. (i) It's a (ii) warm (iii) day (iv) and (v) I want (a) a (b) cup of coffee.<n><n>Output: The answer is B: ii and iii<n><n>Input: In an A+B or A x B relation, is the answer B?<n>Output: Yes<n><n>Input: Input the following set of numbers, and choose your answer from the given choices: 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8 9.<n>Output: The answer should be C: 9<n><n>Input: Input a set of 2 or more numbers 1, 2 2, 3 5 2, 4. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: Mara has 150 - 40 = <<150-40=110>>110 cards.<n>Janet has 110/2 = <<110/2=55>>55 cards since Mara has twice as many as Janet.<n>Brenda has 55 - 9 = <<55-9=46>>46 cards since Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda.<n>Therefore, they all have 110 + 55 + 46 = <<110+55+46=211>>211 cards.<n>So the final answer is 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. He rode the bus 20 blocks to the post office to get some stamps. Later, he came home the same way. How many blocks did Pete travel in all?<n>Output: The number of blocks traveled on the way to the post office was 5 + 20 = <<5+20=25>>25.<n>Pete traveled 25 × 2 = <<25*2=50>>50 blocks in all.<n>So the final answer is 50<n><n>Input: In a classroom, there are blue chairs, green chairs, and white chairs. There are 10 blue chairs. The green chairs are 3 times as many as the blue chairs, and there are 13 fewer white chairs than the green and blue chairs combined. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: There are 10 x 3 = <<10*3=30>>30 green chairs.<n>The total number of blue and green chairs is 10 + 30 = <<10+30=40>>40.<n>So, there are 40 - 13 = <<40-13=27>>27 white chairs.<n>Therefore, there are 40 +27 = <<40+27=67>>67 chairs in a classroom.<n>So the final answer is 67<n><n>Input: 4.5 gallons of coffee were divided among 18 thermoses. Genevieve drank 3 thermoses. How many pints of coffee did Genevieve drink?<n>Output: 4.5 gallons = 4.5 * 8 pints = <<4.5*8=36>>36 pints<n>36/18 = <<36/18=2>>2 pints<n>Genevieve drank 2*3=<<2*3=6>>6 pints of coffee.<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Alannah, Beatrix, and Queen are preparing for the new school year and have been given books by their parents. Alannah has 20 more books than Beatrix. Queen has 1/5 times more books than Alannah. If Beatrix has 30 books, how many books do the three have together?<n>Output: If Beatrix has 30 books, Alannah has 30 books + 20 books = <<30+20=50>>50 books.<n>Queen has 1/5 * 50 books = <<1/5*50=10>>10 more books than Alannah.<n>The total number of books Queen has is 50 books + 10 books = <<50+10=60>>60 books.<n>All three have 60 books + 50 books + 30 books = <<60+50+30=140>>140 books together<n>So the final answer is 140<n><n>Input: A bird eats 7 berries a day. Samuel has 5 birds. How many berries do Samuel's birds eat in 4 days?<n>Output: A bird eats 7 x 4 = <<7*4=28>>28 berries in 4 days.<n>So, 5 birds can eat 28 x 5 = <<28*5=140>>140 berries in 4 days.<n>So the final answer is 140<n><n>Input:The crab was scuttling but strained when he moved, what was impeding him? Choices:  A: verdict B: judging C: responsibility D: evaluating E: prejudice<n>Output:		Judging pigs requires careful responsibility / evaluation/ how can we divide this in half?  Let's find out!<n>A/B = A/B = A/A= A / B = A + B<n>C/D= C/D = D/C = D+C<n><n>A+(D/C) = (2A + D)/C = 2 * (A +B)/C<n><n>E/ C = E/C = (E + C)/C<n><n>2*(A + B)/C + (E + C)/K = 3(2A+B+E+C)/C = C<n><n>C - C/2 = A/B + B/C + C/D + E/C<n><n>A/B + B/c + C/D/E/C = C<n><n>Now that we know what we know, we know we have 5 options<n><n>A = A divided by 2 = A/2 = B/C + B/ A*C = A/2 + B/AC = C<n><n>B/C + B/AC = E/C= E/C (because we made the two A's into one) C<n><n>C/D + E/K = F/K = F/C (Now we found the value of K and E we know what C must equal.<n><n>We can multiply 2, B, and C together to solve for F<n><n>B/C is not an answer so we will put it in the F category.<n><n>F/C = 2B / C <------- (2F/C) = 2B/C = 1<n><n>C/D is also not an option.<n>C/D = C/K + C/D ( We already solved what B is)<n><n>Also, we solved what C is, so we know what D must equal.<n><n>(4C/K)/D = 4 (C/K)+ C/D <-----  C = 1 and D = 2C<n><n>D/E = D/C * D/K = (2C)/K * D/C, But that is 4C/K.<n><n>So D/K = 4D/C<n><n>Hence, D = 1, E = 2C.<n><n>K = 1 or 2C, whatever it

How many pints of coffee did Genevieve drink?<n>Output: 4.5 gallons = 4.5 * 8 pints = <<4.5*8=36>>36 pints<n>36/18 = <<36/18=2>>2 pints<n>Genevieve drank 2*3=<<2*3=6>>6 pints of coffee.<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Alannah, Beatrix, and Queen are preparing for the new school year and have been given books by their parents. If Beatrix has 30 books, how many books do the three have together?<n>Output: If Beatrix has 30 books, Alannah has 30 books + 20 books = <<30+20=50>>50 books.<n>Queen has 1/5 * 50 books = <<1/5*50=10>>10 more books than Alannah.<n>The total number of books Queen has is 50 books + 10 books = <<50+10=60>>60 books.<n>All three have 60 books + 50 books + 30 books = <<60+50+30=140>>140 books together<n>So the final answer is 140<n><n>Input: A bird eats 7 berries a day. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet.
